ry archive encompasses a vast range of voices—young and old, men and women, the pious and the secular, optimists and pessimists—and chronicles different perspectives on the topics of the day while also preserving rapidly endangered cultural traditions. Described by David G. Roskies as “a civilization responding to its own destruction,” these texts tell the story of the Warsaw Ghetto in real time, against time, and for all time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandzWarsawvPersonal narratives. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandzWarsawvSources. 0aJewsxPersecutionszPolandzWarsawxHistoryvSources. 0aJewszPolandzWarsawvBiography. 0aJewszPolandzWarsawxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Jewish. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewszPolandzWarsawvSources. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewszPolandzWarsaw. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aAuerbach, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldin, Leyb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrodzieńska, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuberband, Shimon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Chaim A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKassow, Samuel D.1 aKassow, Samuel D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatzenelson, Yitzhak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirman, Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewin, Abraham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLichtenstein, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaor,, econtributor.4ctb4h